{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17659031","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17659031"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T23:00:18+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T23:00:18+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20842"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20842","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20842"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13717"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97372"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13717","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13717"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20842"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79987"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"11597"},{"type":"tags","id":"12331"},{"type":"tags","id":"12665"},{"type":"tags","id":"12666"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"33026"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33027"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97372","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/97372"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ECancer cells exhibit unique metabolic characteristics that support their rapid growth and proliferation.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the Warburg effect in cancer cells?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Enhanced oxidative phosphorylation with reduced glycolysis","Increased glycolysis despite oxygen availability","Exclusive reliance on ketone bodies for energy production","Decreased glucose uptake with enhanced glutamine metabolism","Increased fatty acid oxidation despite glucose availability"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe Warburg effect refers to \u003Cstrong\u003Eincreased glycolysis despite oxygen availability\u003C/strong\u003E in cancer cells. Even when oxygen is plentiful, cancer cells preferentially metabolise glucose to lactate via glycolysis rather than utilising the more efficient oxidative phosphorylation pathway. This phenomenon, also known as aerobic glycolysis, provides cancer cells with metabolic intermediates needed for biosynthetic pathways that support rapid cell division.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased fatty acid oxidation despite glucose availability\u003C/strong\u003E - While some cancers may utilise fatty acid oxidation, this is not the Warburg effect, which specifically refers to altered glucose metabolism.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEnhanced oxidative phosphorylation with reduced glycolysis\u003C/strong\u003E - This is the opposite of the Warburg effect, which involves increased glycolysis with reduced reliance on oxidative phosphorylation.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDecreased glucose uptake with enhanced glutamine metabolism\u003C/strong\u003E - The Warburg effect is characterised by increased, not decreased, glucose uptake. While glutamine metabolism is important in many cancers, this is not the Warburg effect.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExclusive reliance on ketone bodies for energy production\u003C/strong\u003E - Cancer cells typically do not rely primarily on ketone bodies; the Warburg effect specifically involves glucose metabolism.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe high glucose uptake characteristic of the Warburg effect is exploited clinically in positron emission tomography (PET) scanning, where fluorodeoxyglucose (a glucose analogue) is preferentially taken up by cancer cells, allowing visualisation of tumours.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The Warburg effect describes cancer cells\u0027 preference for glycolysis even when oxygen is present (aerobic glycolysis).","Cancer cells demonstrate increased glucose uptake and conversion to lactate despite adequate oxygen availability.","The Warburg effect is exploited clinically in PET scanning using fluorodeoxyglucose to visualise tumours."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 7; pages 299-300."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79987"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20842"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79987","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/79987"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-06T13:09:53+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-06T13:10:41+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13717"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97372"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11597","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11597"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Neoplasia","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":6,"createdAt":"2025-02-26T20:57:41+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-26T20:57:41+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"18"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"12331","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/12331"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Molec